Aim
To write a C++ program that demonstrates the use of friend function and friend class to access private members of a class.

Algorithm
Start the program.
Create a class with private data members.
Declare a friend function inside the class.
Declare another class as a friend class.
Define the friend function outside the class and access the private members.
In the friend class, create a member function that accesses the private members of the original class.
Create objects and call both the friend function and the friend class function.
Display the results.
End the program.

Program (C++)
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
class A {
private:
    int value;

public:
    A(int v) {
        value = v;
    }

    // Friend function declaration
    friend void showValue(A obj);

    // Friend class declaration
    friend class B;
};

// Friend function definition
void showValue(A obj) {
    cout << "Friend Function: Value = " << obj.value << endl;
}

class B {
public:
    // Function inside friend class accessing private members of A
    void display(A obj) {
        cout << "Friend Class: Value = " << obj.value << endl;
    }
};

int main() {
    A objA(100);  // create object
    B objB;       // create object of friend class

    // Calling friend function
    showValue(objA);

    // Calling friend class function
    objB.display(objA);

    return 0;
}

Sample Output (Result)
Friend Function: Value = 100
Friend Class: Value = 100

Result
Thus, the program successfully illustrates the use of both:
Friend Function
Friend Class
to access private members of another class.
